# Lesson candidate — a custom tzinfo whose utcoffset() calls astimezone() recurses; a naive caller masks it

**Date:** 2026-06-28
**Surfaced by:** conductor fire c8f2465 (while shipping the BOLD-FLEET-PRODUCER-KEYSTONE first slice).

## Symptom
The exact production invocation `python automation/state/fleet/build_shared_signal.py`
(how `run-fleet-executor.ps1` calls it) crashed with `RecursionError: maximum recursion
depth exceeded` — `[Previous line repeated 994 more times]` at `et_clock.py:97`. No crash
in any test that used `et_now()`; only the producer's DEFAULT-now path crashed.

## Root cause
`et_clock._EasternTZ.utcoffset(dt)` did, for an aware `dt`:
`utc_approx = dt.astimezone(timezone.utc)`. But `datetime.astimezone(utc)` must call
`dt.utcoffset()` to convert — and when `dt.tzinfo is self` (the same `_EasternTZ`), that
re-enters `_EasternTZ.utcoffset` → which calls `astimezone` again → infinite recursion.
A `tzinfo` cannot compute its own offset by asking the datetime to convert itself.

## Why it stayed latent (the dangerous part)
`et_now()` returns a **naive** ET datetime, so almost every caller passed naive values →
the naive branch (build `utc_approx` from wall-clock components) never recursed. The ONLY
trigger is an **aware** ET_TZ datetime (`datetime.now(utc).astimezone(ET_TZ)`, then any
`utcoffset()` / `astimezone()` / `strftime("%z")`). `build_shared_signal.build()`'s default
`now` is exactly that aware form, and `written_at = now.strftime("...%z")` hit it. The bug
landed in the TZ-systemic wiring commit (50071b4, 2026-06-26 18:42) AFTER the last RTH, so
it never ran in production — it was a Monday-open timebomb that would have frozen
`shared-signal.json` and blinded the live paper fleet.

## Fix (root, in et_clock — protects all 9+ live paths)
In `utcoffset`, treat `dt.tzinfo is None OR dt.tzinfo is self` identically: build the DST-
lookup proxy from the wall-clock components (no `astimezone`). Only a *foreign*-zone aware
dt takes the `astimezone` branch (its tzinfo's `utcoffset` never calls back into ET_TZ).

## Principle / watch-out
A custom `tzinfo.utcoffset()` must NEVER call `dt.astimezone(...)` (or anything that needs
`dt.utcoffset()`) on a datetime whose `tzinfo is self` — that is an infinite recursion by
construction. Compute the offset from the wall-clock fields directly. And: **a naive-only
caller base masks an aware-path crash** — when a clock utility supports both naive and aware
inputs, a test that only exercises naive inputs is not coverage; exercise the aware path too.

## Detection / encoded-in
`backtest/tests/test_et_clock.py::test_aware_et_tz_datetime_does_not_recurse` (bite-tested
non-vacuous: the pre-fix code recurses). Reproduce a production crash by running the script
as `__main__`, not just by calling helpers with synthetic naive fixtures.

